Certainly! I can suggest code for the rotate method in FilteredFilePOJOViewModel to rotate the image 90 degrees clockwise and save it with the same file name, replacing the existing file. Here's a implementation that should work well with your existing codebase:

```java
public void rotate() {
    if (isRotated.getValue() != AsyncTaskStatus.NOT_YET_STARTED) return;
    isRotated.setValue(AsyncTaskStatus.STARTED);
    ExecutorService executorService = MyExecutorService.getExecutorService();
    future5 = executorService.submit(new Runnable() {
        @Override
        public void run() {
            String file_path = currently_shown_file.getPath();
            try {
                Bitmap originalBitmap = BitmapFactory.decodeFile(file_path);
                Matrix matrix = new Matrix();
                matrix.postRotate(90);
                Bitmap rotatedBitmap = Bitmap.createBitmap(originalBitmap, 0, 0, 
                    originalBitmap.getWidth(), originalBitmap.getHeight(), matrix, true);

                FileOutputStream out = new FileOutputStream(file_path);
                rotatedBitmap.compress(Bitmap.CompressFormat.JPEG, 100, out);
                out.flush();
                out.close();

                // Update the file's last modified time
                new File(file_path).setLastModified(System.currentTimeMillis());

                // Update the FilePOJO object
                currently_shown_file.setDateLong(System.currentTimeMillis());
                currently_shown_file.setDate(Global.SDF.format(System.currentTimeMillis()));

                originalBitmap.recycle();
                rotatedBitmap.recycle();
            } catch (IOException e) {
                e.printStackTrace();
            }
            isRotated.postValue(AsyncTaskStatus.COMPLETED);
        }
    });
}
```

This implementation does the following:

1. Decodes the image file into a Bitmap.
2. Creates a Matrix to perform the rotation.
3. Rotates the Bitmap 90 degrees clockwise.
4. Saves the rotated Bitmap back to the same file path, effectively replacing the original file.
5. Updates the file's last modified time.
6. Updates the FilePOJO object with the new modification time.
7. Recycles the Bitmaps to free up memory.

This code should integrate well with your existing FilteredFilePOJOViewModel and ImageViewFragment.

