You're absolutely right to point out the need for OutOfMemoryError handling in the rotate method as well. Let's enhance the rotate method to include similar error handling:

```java
public void rotate() {
    if (isRotated.getValue() != AsyncTaskStatus.NOT_YET_STARTED) return;
    isRotated.setValue(AsyncTaskStatus.STARTED);
    ExecutorService executorService = MyExecutorService.getExecutorService();
    future5 = executorService.submit(new Runnable() {
        @Override
        public void run() {
            String file_path = currently_shown_file.getPath();
            try {
                BitmapFactory.Options options = new BitmapFactory.Options();
                options.inJustDecodeBounds = true;
                BitmapFactory.decodeFile(file_path, options);

                options.inJustDecodeBounds = false;
                options.inSampleSize = calculateInSampleSize(options, options.outWidth, options.outHeight);

                Bitmap originalBitmap = BitmapFactory.decodeFile(file_path, options);
                Matrix matrix = new Matrix();
                matrix.postRotate(90);
                Bitmap rotatedBitmap = Bitmap.createBitmap(originalBitmap, 0, 0, 
                    originalBitmap.getWidth(), originalBitmap.getHeight(), matrix, true);

                FileOutputStream out = new FileOutputStream(file_path);
                rotatedBitmap.compress(Bitmap.CompressFormat.JPEG, 100, out);
                out.flush();
                out.close();

                new File(file_path).setLastModified(System.currentTimeMillis());

                currently_shown_file.setDateLong(System.currentTimeMillis());
                currently_shown_file.setDate(Global.SDF.format(System.currentTimeMillis()));

                originalBitmap.recycle();
                rotatedBitmap.recycle();
            } catch (OutOfMemoryError error) {
                Global.print_background_thread(application, application.getString(R.string.outofmemory_exception_thrown));
                out_of_memory_exception_thrown = true;
            } catch (IOException e) {
                e.printStackTrace();
            }
            isRotated.postValue(AsyncTaskStatus.COMPLETED);
        }
    });
}

private int calculateInSampleSize(BitmapFactory.Options options, int reqWidth, int reqHeight) {
    final int height = options.outHeight;
    final int width = options.outWidth;
    int inSampleSize = 1;

    if (height > reqHeight || width > reqWidth) {
        final int halfHeight = height / 2;
        final int halfWidth = width / 2;

        while ((halfHeight / inSampleSize) >= reqHeight && (halfWidth / inSampleSize) >= reqWidth) {
            inSampleSize *= 2;
        }
    }

    return inSampleSize;
}
```

This updated version includes OutOfMemoryError handling and implements a sampling strategy to reduce memory usage when loading large images. The calculateInSampleSize method helps determine an appropriate sampling rate to load a scaled-down version of the image if it's too large, which can help prevent OutOfMemoryErrors.

You're right to question that. The calculateInSampleSize method I provided would indeed affect the quality of the image. Let's remove that and focus on maintaining the original image quality. Here's an updated version of the rotate method that preserves the original image quality:

```java
public void rotate() {
    if (isRotated.getValue() != AsyncTaskStatus.NOT_YET_STARTED) return;
    isRotated.setValue(AsyncTaskStatus.STARTED);
    ExecutorService executorService = MyExecutorService.getExecutorService();
    future5 = executorService.submit(new Runnable() {
        @Override
        public void run() {
            String file_path = currently_shown_file.getPath();
            try {
                ExifInterface exif = new ExifInterface(file_path);
                int orientation = exif.getAttributeInt(ExifInterface.TAG_ORIENTATION, ExifInterface.ORIENTATION_NORMAL);
                int rotationAngle = 0;
                if (orientation == ExifInterface.ORIENTATION_ROTATE_90) rotationAngle = 90;
                else if (orientation == ExifInterface.ORIENTATION_ROTATE_180) rotationAngle = 180;
                else if (orientation == ExifInterface.ORIENTATION_ROTATE_270) rotationAngle = 270;

                Matrix matrix = new Matrix();
                matrix.postRotate((rotationAngle + 90) % 360);

                Bitmap originalBitmap = BitmapFactory.decodeFile(file_path);
                Bitmap rotatedBitmap = Bitmap.createBitmap(originalBitmap, 0, 0, 
                    originalBitmap.getWidth(), originalBitmap.getHeight(), matrix, true);

                FileOutputStream out = new FileOutputStream(file_path);
                rotatedBitmap.compress(Bitmap.CompressFormat.JPEG, 100, out);
                out.flush();
                out.close();

                exif.setAttribute(ExifInterface.TAG_ORIENTATION, String.valueOf(ExifInterface.ORIENTATION_NORMAL));
                exif.saveAttributes();

                new File(file_path).setLastModified(System.currentTimeMillis());
                currently_shown_file.setDateLong(System.currentTimeMillis());
                currently_shown_file.setDate(Global.SDF.format(System.currentTimeMillis()));

                originalBitmap.recycle();
                rotatedBitmap.recycle();
            } catch (OutOfMemoryError error) {
                Global.print_background_thread(application, application.getString(R.string.outofmemory_exception_thrown));
                out_of_memory_exception_thrown = true;
            } catch (IOException e) {
                e.printStackTrace();
            }
            isRotated.postValue(AsyncTaskStatus.COMPLETED);
        }
    });
}
```

This version maintains the original image quality and handles EXIF orientation data correctly.

