            try {
                Bitmap originalBitmap = BitmapFactory.decodeFile(file_path);
                if (originalBitmap == null) {
                    throw new IOException("Failed to decode bitmap");
                }

                Matrix matrix = new Matrix();
                matrix.postRotate(90);

                Bitmap rotatedBitmap = Bitmap.createBitmap(originalBitmap, 0, 0, 
                    originalBitmap.getWidth(), originalBitmap.getHeight(), matrix, true);

                file.delete(); // Ensure old file is removed

                FileOutputStream out = new FileOutputStream(file);
                rotatedBitmap.compress(Bitmap.CompressFormat.JPEG, 100, out);
                out.flush();
                out.close();

                ExifInterface exif = new ExifInterface(file_path);
                exif.setAttribute(ExifInterface.TAG_ORIENTATION, String.valueOf(ExifInterface.ORIENTATION_NORMAL));
                exif.saveAttributes();

                file.setLastModified(System.currentTimeMillis());
                currently_shown_file.setDateLong(System.currentTimeMillis());
                currently_shown_file.setDate(Global.SDF.format(System.currentTimeMillis()));

                // Update media store
                MediaScannerConnection.scanFile(application, new String[]{file_path}, null, null);

                originalBitmap.recycle();
                rotatedBitmap.recycle();
            } catch (Exception e) {
                e.printStackTrace();
            }
            isRotated.postValue(AsyncTaskStatus.COMPLETED);
        }
    });
}
```

This updated method should address the potential issues and successfully rotate the image. If the problem persists, we may need to investigate further into device-specific issues or file system permissions.

Certainly, I'll review the file saving portion of the rotate method. Based on the provided codebase context, here's an enhanced version of the rotate method that should ensure the changes are properly written to the file:

```java
public void rotate() {
    if (isRotated.getValue() != AsyncTaskStatus.NOT_YET_STARTED) return;
    isRotated.setValue(AsyncTaskStatus.STARTED);
    ExecutorService executorService = MyExecutorService.getExecutorService();
    future5 = executorService.submit(new Runnable() {
        @Override
        public void run() {
            String file_path = currently_shown_file.getPath();
            File file = new File(file_path);
            try {
                Bitmap originalBitmap = BitmapFactory.decodeFile(file_path);
                Matrix matrix = new Matrix();
                matrix.postRotate(90);
                Bitmap rotatedBitmap = Bitmap.createBitmap(originalBitmap, 0, 0, 
                    originalBitmap.getWidth(), originalBitmap.getHeight(), matrix, true);

                // Use a temporary file to ensure complete write
                File tempFile = new File(file.getParentFile(), "temp_" + file.getName());
                FileOutputStream out = new FileOutputStream(tempFile);
                rotatedBitmap.compress(Bitmap.CompressFormat.JPEG, 100, out);
                out.flush();
                out.close();

                // Replace the original file with the temp file
                if (tempFile.exists() && tempFile.length() > 0) {
                    if (file.delete() && tempFile.renameTo(file)) {
                        // Update file metadata
                        file.setLastModified(System.currentTimeMillis());
                        currently_shown_file.setDateLong(System.currentTimeMillis());
                        currently_shown_file.setDate(Global.SDF.format(System.currentTimeMillis()));

                        // Update media store
                        MediaScannerConnection.scanFile(application, 
                            new String[]{file_path}, null, null);
                    }
                }

                originalBitmap.recycle();
                rotatedBitmap.recycle();
            } catch (Exception e) {
                e.printStackTrace();
            }
            isRotated.postValue(AsyncTaskStatus.COMPLETED);
        }
    });
}
```

This revised method uses a temporary file to ensure the write operation completes successfully before replacing the original file. It also includes error checking and updates the media store to ensure other apps can see the changes.

To add a fast scroll to a RecyclerView in Android, you can follow these steps:

1. Set the `fastScrollEnabled` attribute to true in your RecyclerView XML:

```xml
<androidx.recyclerview.widget.RecyclerView
    android:id="@+id/recyclerview"
    android:layout_width="match_parent"
    android:layout_height="match_parent"
    android:fastScrollEnabled="true"
    android:fastScrollVerticalThumbDrawable="@drawable/thumb_drawable"
    android:fastScrollVerticalTrackDrawable="@drawable/line_drawable" />
```

2. Create custom drawables for the thumb and track (optional):
   - `thumb_drawable.xml`: for the scrollbar thumb
   - `line_drawable.xml`: for the scrollbar track

3. In your RecyclerView adapter, implement the `SectionIndexer` interface:

```java
public class YourAdapter extends RecyclerView.Adapter<YourViewHolder> implements SectionIndexer {
    // Implement methods from SectionIndexer
    @Override
    public Object[] getSections() {
        // Return an array of your section headers
    }

    @Override
    public int getPositionForSection(int sectionIndex) {
        // Return the position for a given section
    }

    @Override
    public int getSectionForPosition(int position) {
        // Return the section index for a given position
    }
}
```

4. Set up your RecyclerView with a LinearLayoutManager and attach your adapter:

```java
RecyclerView recyclerView = findViewById(R.id.recyclerview);
recyclerView.setLayoutManager(new LinearLayoutManager(this));
YourAdapter adapter = new YourAdapter(yourDataList);
recyclerView.setAdapter(adapter);
```

By implementing these steps, you'll add a fast scroll feature to your RecyclerView, allowing users to quickly navigate through large lists of items.
